23    /**
24    * Factory class that can provide serializers for any regular Java beans
25    * (as defined by "having at least one get method recognizable as bean
26    * accessor" -- where {@link Object#getClass} does not count);
27    * as well as for "standard" JDK types. Latter is achieved
28    * by delegating calls to {@link BasicSerializerFactory}
29    * to find serializers both for "standard" JDK types (and in some cases,
30    * sub-classes as is the case for collection classes like
31    * {@link java.util.List}s and {@link java.util.Map}s) and bean (value)
32    * classes.
33    *<p>
34    * Note about delegating calls to {@link BasicSerializerFactory}:
35    * although it would be nicer to use linear delegation
36    * for construction (to essentially dispatch all calls first to the
37    * underlying {@link BasicSerializerFactory}; or alternatively after
38    * failing to provide bean-based serializer}, there is a problem:
39    * priority levels for detecting standard types are mixed. That is,
40    * we want to check if a type is a bean after some of "standard" JDK
41    * types, but before the rest.
42    * As a result, "mixed" delegation used, and calls are NOT done using
43    * regular {@link SerializerFactory} interface but rather via
44    * direct calls to {@link BasicSerializerFactory}.
45    *<p>
46    * Finally, since all caching is handled by the serializer provider
47    * (not factory) and there is no configurability, this
48    * factory is stateless.
49    * This means that a global singleton instance can be used.
50    */
